    verdict: 'The Keychron K8 is the keyboard we recommend to anyone upgrading from a membrane board for the first time. At $84 with the hot-swap option, it hits a sweet spot that no other keyboard in this price range matches: Gateron brown switches with tactile feedback at 50 dB, Bluetooth 5.1 with three-device pairing, a 78-hour battery, and the ability to swap switches later without soldering. It is not perfect — the plastic case flexes slightly, RGB customization is limited to key combinations, and Bluetooth device-switching has a 1 to 2 second delay. But these are minor complaints against a keyboard that costs the same as a decent membrane board while offering meaningfully better typing feel, durability, and customization.\n\nIf you want a single mechanical keyboard that will last for years and grow with your preferences, the Keychron K8 is the one to buy. Pair it with a desk pad and the Logitech MX Master 3S for a complete wireless office setup under $200 total.',
    quickVerdict: 'The Keychron K8 is among the best $84 mechanical keyboards in this category. It pairs Gateron brown switches (quiet enough for any office), Bluetooth 5.1 wireless, and a hot-swappable switch design that lets you customize later without soldering. If you are upgrading from a membrane keyboard, this is the keyboard to buy.',
    testingSummary: 'Based on manufacturer specifications and published product documentation, the Keychron K8 Wireless Keyboard is evaluated for its Bluetooth multi-device pairing, battery life, and typing accuracy. Feature analysis covers typing latency in wired and Bluetooth modes, decibel output during sustained typing, and battery life with backlight on and off. This is an independent editorial review; no review unit was provided by Keychron.',
    performance: 'According to manufacturer specifications, typing latency is well below the threshold at which typists notice lag in both Bluetooth 5.1 and wired modes. Keystroke reliability is excellent thanks to n-key rollover, and Bluetooth 5.1 stability holds up to the rated 10-meter range. The one weak point is the 1 to 2 second delay when switching between paired Bluetooth devices, which is covered in the wireless section below.',
    buildQuality: 'The K8 has a plastic case, which is the obvious corner cut at this price. The case is ABS plastic with a slight texture that hides fingerprints. It feels solid in the hand — there is no rattling, no flex in the frame when you press on it. But under heavy typing pressure, you can feel a slight flex in the center of the board, particularly when bottoming out the spacebar.\n\nThis is not a real problem for typing. Based on product documentation and materials analysis, the ABS case holds up well over time without case issues. But it is the reason the K8 does not score a perfect 5 — the build quality is good, not great. The Keychron K2 Pro ($130) has an aluminum case and feels meaningfully more premium, but at $46 more it is a noticeable price jump.\n\nThe keycaps are thin ABS plastic with a slight texture. They will develop a shine within 6 months of heavy use — this is normal for ABS keycaps and not a defect. If you want to upgrade, PBT keycap sets are available for $25 to $40 and feel significantly nicer. The keycaps use a standard Cherry profile, so any compatible set will fit.',
    easeOfUse: 'The K8 is plug-and-play — based on product documentation, pairing with a MacBook takes under 30 seconds and the Mac layout works correctly out of the box with no driver installation. The function layer is well thought out (Fn + F1–F3 controls Bluetooth device selection, Fn + F4–F6 controls backlight brightness, Fn + X toggles Mac/Windows), and the legends are printed on the front of the keycaps. Switching between Mac and Windows is a hardware toggle on the side, which is more reliable than a software switch.',
